{"title_page": "77th Indian Infantry Brigade", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 77th Indian Infantry Brigade<br>77th Indian Parachute Brigade\n|abbreviation=\n|image=\n|caption=\n|dates= 1942\u20131945\n|country= {{flagicon|British Raj}} [[British Raj|British India]]\n|allegiance= {{flag|British Empire}}\n|branch= [[File:British Raj Red Ensign.svg|23px]] [[British Indian Army]]\n|type= [[Infantry]]<br>[[Airborne forces]]\n|role= [[Paratrooper|Parachute infantry]]\n|size= [[Brigade]]\n|command_structure=\n|equipment=\n<!-- Commanders -->\n|Past Commanders=\n|ceremonial_chief=\n|colonel_of_the_regiment=\n|notable_commanders= [[Orde Wingate]]<br>[[Mike Calvert]]\n<!-- Insignia -->\n|identification_symbol=\n|identification_symbol_2=\n<!-- Culture and history -->\n|nickname=\n|patron=\n|motto=\n|colors=\n|march=\n|mascot=\n|battles=\n|anniversaries=\n|decorations=\n|battle_honours=\n}}\nThe '''77th Indian Infantry Brigade''' was an [[infantry]] [[brigade]] formation of the [[Indian Army during World War II]]. It was formed in [[British Raj|India]] in June 1942. The brigade was assigned to the [[Chindits]] and organised into eight columns for operations behind enemy lines in Burma. In March 1945, it was converted into the 77th Indian Parachute Brigade and assigned to the [[44th Airborne Division (India)|44th Airborne Division]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2009-10-19|publisher=Order of Battle|title=77 Brigade|url=http://www.ordersofbattle.com/UnitData.aspx?UniX=6171&Tab=Uhi}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n===1942\u20131943===\n* 13th Battalion, [[King's Regiment (Liverpool)]]\n* 3rd Battalion, [[2nd Gurkha Rifles]]\n* 2nd Battalion, [[Burma Rifles]]\n* 3rd Battalion, [[9th Gurkha Rifles]] January 1944\u2013August 1944\n* 12th Battalion, [[Nigeria Regiment]] April 1944\u2013May 1944\n* 7th Battalion, Nigeria Regiment April 1944\u2013May 1944\n\n===1943\u20131945===\n* 3rd Battalion, [[6th Gurkha Rifles]]\n* 1st Battalion, [[King's Regiment (Liverpool)]]\n* 1st Battalion, [[Lancashire Fusiliers]]\n* 1st Battalion, [[South Staffordshire Regiment]]<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2009-10-19|publisher=Order of Battle|title=77 Brigade Subordanates|url=http://www.ordersofbattle.com/UnitData.aspx?UniX=10073&Tab=Sub}}</ref>\n\n===77th Parachute Brigade===\n* [[15th (King's) Parachute Battalion]]\n* [[16th (Staffords) Parachute Battalion]]\n* 2nd Battalion, [[Parachute Regiment (India)|Indian Parachute Regiment]]\n* 4th Battalion, Indian Parachute Regiment <ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2009-10-19|publisher=Order of Battle|title=77 Parachute Brigade Subordanates|url=http://www.ordersofbattle.com/UnitData.aspx?UniX=6203&Tab=Sub|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130104082317/http://www.ordersofbattle.com/UnitData.aspx?UniX=6203&Tab=Sub|archive-date=2013-01-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|World War II}}\n* [[List of Indian Army Brigades in World War II]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:British Indian Army brigades]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations in Burma in World War II]]\n\n\n{{India-mil-unit-stub}}\n{{WWII-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 77th Indian Infantry Brigade<br>77th Indian Parachute Brigade\n|abbreviation=\n|image=\n|caption=\n|dates= 1942&ndash;1945\n|country= {{flagicon|British Raj}} [[British Raj|British India]]\n|allegiance= {{flag|British Empire}}\n|branch= [[File:British Raj Red Ensign.svg|23px]] [[British Indian Army]]\n|type= [[Infantry]]<br>[[Airborne forces]]\n|role= [[Paratrooper|Parachute infantry]]\n|size= [[Brigade]]\n|command_structure= \n|equipment= \n<!-- Commanders -->\n|Past Commanders=\n|ceremonial_chief=\n|colonel_of_the_regiment=\n|notable_commanders= [[Orde Wingate]]<br>[[Mike Calvert]]\n<!-- Insignia -->\n|identification_symbol=\n|identification_symbol_2=\n<!-- Culture and history -->\n|nickname= \n|patron=\n|motto= \n|colors=\n|march=\n|mascot=\n|battles=\n|anniversaries=\n|decorations=\n|battle_honours=\n}}\nThe '''77th Indian Infantry Brigade''' was an [[infantry]] [[brigade]] formation of the [[Indian Army during World War II]]. It was formed in [[British Raj|India]] in June 1942. The brigade was assigned to the [[Chindits]] and organised into eight columns for operations behind enemy lines in Burma. In March 1945, it was converted into the 77th Indian Parachute Brigade and assigned to the [[44th Airborne Division (India)|44th Airborne Division]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2009-10-19|publisher=Order of Battle|title=77 Brigade|url=http://www.ordersofbattle.com/UnitData.aspx?UniX=6171&Tab=Uhi}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n===1942&ndash;1943===\n*13th Battalion, [[King's Regiment (Liverpool)]]\n*3rd Battalion, [[2nd Gurkha Rifles]]\n*2nd Battalion, [[Burma Rifles]]\n*3rd Battalion, [[9th Gurkha Rifles]] January 1944&ndash;August 1944\n*12th Battalion, [[Nigeria Regiment]] April 1944&ndash;May 1944\n*7th Battalion, Nigeria Regiment April 1944&ndash;May 1944\n\n===1943&ndash;1945===\n*3rd Battalion, [[6th Gurkha Rifles]]\n*1st Battalion, [[King's Regiment (Liverpool)]]\n*1st Battalion, [[Lancashire Fusiliers]]\n*1st Battalion, [[South Staffordshire Regiment]]<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2009-10-19|publisher=Order of Battle|title=77 Brigade Subordanates|url=http://www.ordersofbattle.com/UnitData.aspx?UniX=10073&Tab=Sub}}</ref>\n\n===77th Parachute Brigade===\n*[[15th (King's) Parachute Battalion]]\n*[[16th (Staffords) Parachute Battalion]]\n*2nd Battalion, [[Parachute Regiment (India)|Indian Parachute Regiment]]\n*4th Battalion, Indian Parachute Regiment <ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2009-10-19|publisher=Order of Battle|title=77 Parachute Brigade Subordanates|url=http://www.ordersofbattle.com/UnitData.aspx?UniX=6203&Tab=Sub|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130104082317/http://www.ordersofbattle.com/UnitData.aspx?UniX=6203&Tab=Sub|archive-date=2013-01-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|World War II}}\n* [[List of Indian Army Brigades in World War II]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:British Indian Army brigades]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations in Burma in World War II]]\n\n\n{{India-mil-unit-stub}}\n{{WWII-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Eastfarthingan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/77th_Indian_Infantry_Brigade"}
{"title_page": "List of twin towns and sister cities in Greece", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n[[File:GreeceOMC.png|right|thumb|280px|Map of Greece]]\n[[File:Rethymno town twinnings.jpg|left|thumb|240px|[[Rethymno]]'s twin towns in 2006]]\n__NOTOC__\nThis is a list of places in Greece having standing links to local communities in other countries. In most cases, the association, especially when formalised by local government, is known as \"[[town twinning]]\" (though other terms, such as \"partner towns\" or \"sister cities\" are sometimes used instead), and while most of the places included are towns, the list also comprises villages, cities, districts, counties, etc. with similar links. In [[Greece|Greek]], the word ''\u03b1\u03b4\u03b5\u03bb\u03c6\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03af\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7 / adelfopiisi'' (fraternisation) has been adopted.\n\n{{compact ToC| side=yes | name=Index | nobreak=yes | center=yes | align=center | seealso=no | notes=no | refs=yes | extlinks=no}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==A==\n'''[[Agia Paraskevi]]'''<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u0391\u03b3. \u03a0\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03c3\u03ba\u03b5\u03c5\u03b7\u03c2: \u0395\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03ba\u03b5\u03c8\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03c2 \u03b1\u03b4\u03b5\u03bb\u03c6\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03b9\u03b7\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 Saint-Brieuc \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0393\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03ba\u03b7\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5|url=https://www.agiaparaskevi.gr/portal/index.php/nea/nea-tou-dimou/4401-dimos-ag-paraskevis-episkepseis-stis-adelfopoiimenes-poleis-saint-brieuc-kai-geroskipou|website=agiaparaskevi.gr|publisher=Agia Paraskevi|language=el|date=2017-09-27|accessdate=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*{{flagicon|CYP}} [[Geroskipou]], Cyprus\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Saint-Brieuc]], France\n{{div col end}}\n\n'''[[Aigio]]'''<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0391\u03b4\u03b5\u03bb\u