rtv.sm|publisher=San Marino RTV|language=it|date=2014-09-28|accessdate=2020-01-11}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Yevpatoria]], Ukraine<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0421 \u043a\u0435\u043c \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0430\u0442 \u0434\u0430\u0432\u043d\u043e \u0438 \u043d\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0436\u0438\u0432\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u0441\u0432\u044f\u0437\u0438 \u0441\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044f \u043a\u0440\u044b\u043c\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430|url=https://gazetacrimea.ru/news/s-kem-dryjat-davno-i-nalajivaut-svyazi-segodnya-krimskie-goroda-29620|website=gazetacrimea.ru|publisher=Gazeta Crimea|language=ru|date=2018-04-27|accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n'''[[Zitsa]]'''<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0391\u03b4\u03b5\u03bb\u03c6\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03af\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7 \u0394\u03ae\u03bc\u03bf\u03c5 \u0396\u03af\u03c4\u03c3\u03b1\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0394\u03ae\u03bc\u03bf Nardo \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03ac\u03c4\u03c9 \u0399\u03c4\u03b1\u03bb\u03af\u03b1\u03c2|url=https://www.zitsa.gov.gr/culture/adelpopoieseis-5/4-adelpopoiese-demou-zitsas-me-ton-demo-nardo-tes-kato-italias|website=zitsa.gov.gr|publisher=Zitsa|language=el|accessdate=2020-01-11}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Nard\u00f2]], Italy\n\n==References==\n<small>{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}</small>\n\n{{Twin towns}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List of twin towns and sister cities in Greece}}\n[[Category:Lists of twin towns and sister cities in Europe|Greece]]\n[[Category:Greece geography-related lists|Twin towns]]\n", "name_user": "FromCzech", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eZ", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_twin_towns_and_sister_cities_in_Greece"}
{"title_page": "Jella Lepman", "text_new": "[[File:Gedenktafel Jella Lepman.jpg|thumb|Memorial plaque for Jella Lepman at the international youth library in Blutenburg castel]]\n\n'''Jella Lepman''' (15 May 1891, in [[Stuttgart]] \u2013 14 October 1970, in [[Zurich]]) was a [[Germany|German]] journalist, author and translator who founded the [[International Youth Library]] in Munich.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.freiburger-rundbrief.de/de/?item=231 | title=Jella Lepman \u2014 Die Kinderbuchbr\u00fccke | author=Ingrid Wei\u00df | date=1995 | website= | publisher=Freiburger Rundbrief | language=German | accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\nJella Lehman, born in [[Stuttgart]], was the oldest daughter of the manufacturer Josef Lehmann (1853-1911) and his wife Flora ([[n\u00e9e]] Lauchheimer; 1867-1940). The family were members of the [[Reform Judaism|Jewish-liberal Judaism]]. Through her mother she was a cousin of the four-year younger [[Max Horkheimer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.juedische-allgemeine.de/unsere-woche/die-kinder-werden-den-weg-zeigen/|title=\u00bbDie Kinder werden den Weg zeigen\u00ab |accessdate=April 1, 2020|date=August 25, 2019|work=J\u00fcdische Allgemeine| author=Diehl, Kathrin |}}</ref> After her schooling at the K\u00f6nigin-Katharina-Stift-Gymnasium in Stuttgart, she spent a year near [[Lausanne]], Switzerland. At the age of 17, in 1908, she organised an international reading room for the children of foreign works at a tobacco factory in an industrial quarter of Stuttgart.\n\nIn 1913 she married Gustav Horace Lepman (1877-1922), the German-American co-owner of a bedspring factory in [[Stuttgart-Feuerbach]]. Together they had two children: (Anne-Marie, born in 1918, G\u00fcnther, born in 1921). During the [[World War I]] Gustav Lepman served as an officer in the German army on the battlefields in France. He died as the result of his war injuries in 1922, leaving her widowed at age 31.\n \nAfter the death of her husband, Jella Lepman became editor of the ''Stuttgarter Neues Tagblatt'', the first woman ever to hold this position. She wrote socio-political contributions and in 1927 introduced the newspaper supplement for women titled  \"The woman in house, profession and society\". In addition, she published her first children's book (1927 ''The Sleeping Sunday'') and a theatrical play for children (1929 ''The Singing Pfennig'') which was performed on the smaller state of the W\u00fcrttemberg State Theatre. She became a member of the [[German Democratic Party]] (''Deutsche Demokratische Partei'', DDP), where she was a leader in the women's group. In 1929, she ran, unsuccessfully, for the German [[Reichstag (Weimar Republic)|Reichstag]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.stadtlexikon-stuttgart.de/article/d6a07d28-640b-4bcb-b202-a823655f6cbd/Jella_Lepman_%281891-1970%29.html | title=Jella Lepman (1891 \u2013 1970) |accessdate=April 1, 2020|date=April 19, 2018| work=Stadtlexikon| author=Ferchl, Irene |language=de}}</ref>\n\nWith the [[Nazi seizure of power]] in 1933, Jella Lepman, as a Jew, lost her job at the newspaper, but was able to continue working for it as a freelancer until 1935. In 1936, she emigrated with her two children via Italy to [[England]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.zeit.de/2013/07/Geschichte-Stuttgart-1921/seite-3 | title=Stuttgart 1921 | author=J\u00f6rg Schweigard | date= | website= | publisher=ZEIT ONLINE | language=German | accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref> With her children cared for in boarding schools, she initially took on freelance journalistic and literary assignments. In 1938 she helped organise the papers of [[Arthur Schnitzler]] which had recently arrived at the [[University of Cambridge]]. Later, she worked for the [[BBC]] and the [[American Broadcasting Station in Europe]] (ABSIE). In 1942 she published a German-language reader titled '' Die Kinder vom Kuckuckshof, eine Detektivgeschichte aus dem Schwarzwald '' for the publisher [[John Murray (publisher)|John Murray]] and in 1943, under the [[pseudonym]] Katherine Thomas, the book '' Women in Nazi Germany ''.\n\n== After the war ==\nAfter the end of [[World War II]], she returned to Germany in October 1945 as a consultant to the [[United States Army|US Army]] as part of the {{ill|Reeducation (denazification)|lt=Reeducation|de|Reeducation}} program of the American occupied zone,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://libreas.eu/ausgabe25/05becchi/ | title=Jella Lepman: Die Gr\u00fcnderin der Internationalen Jugendbibliothek | author=Anna Becchi | date=2014 | website= | publisher=LIBREAS. Library Ideas | language=German | accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref> and responsible for programmes for women and youth. She lived first in [[Bad Homburg vor der H\u00f6he]], then in [[Munich]]. In 1946 she organised the first international exhibition in post-war Germany, the {{ill|Internationale Jugendbuchausstellung |lt=Internationale Jugendbuchausstellung|de|Internationale Jugendbuchausstellung}}, which displayed 2000 books from 14 countries. It was shown in several large cities around Germany and visited by over one million people. These books became the founding collection for the [[International Youth Library]] which was opened in the [[Schwabing]] section of Munich 14 September 1949. She remained its director until her retirement in 1957.\n\nDuring the [[reconstruction of Germany]], she was convinced that placing books into the hands of the children would offer them hope for the future. In 1952 she initiated a conference about international understanding through children's books, which led to the foundation of the non-profit [[International Board on Books for Young People]] in [[Zurich]] in 1953. Lepman wrote more in detail about this time of her life in her autobiographical book ''A Bridge of Children's Books''. She was one of the initiators of the [[Hans Christian Andersen Award]], the world's most important award for writers and illustrators of young people's literature. It was first issued in 1956, and she served as its jury president from 1956 to 1960.\n\nJella Lepman wrote many children\u2019s books and collections of children\u2019s stories, including a multivolume collection of bedtime stories that she collected over the years. Her books have been translated into many different languages. She gave her friend [[Erich K\u00e4stner]] the idea that inspired his children's book ''The Animals' Conference'' (''Die Konferenz der Tiere'', 1949).\n\nLepman died in 1970 at the age of 79 years in Zurich and her final resting place was in the [[Zurich Enzenb\u00fchl cemetery]] on Forchstra\u00dfe. The grave no longer exists.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/prd/de/index/bevoelkerungsamt/tod/friedhoefe/prominente_verstorbene.html | title=Prominente Vorstorbene nach Alphabet (PDF) |accessdate=April 1, 2020|date=March 6, 2020| work=Stadt Z\u00fcrich| language=de}}</ref> There is a street named after her in Stuttgart, and a room named after her in Stuttgart's main public library on Mail\u00e4nder-Platz. In Munich a street and a child-care centre are named after her in the city quarter of Berg am Laim.\n\nSince 1991, in honor of Lepman's 100th birthday, the International Board on Books for Young People awards the \"Jella-Lepman Medal\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=737 | title=Jella Lepman Medal | author= | date= | website= | publisher=International Board on Books for Young People | language= | accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref> to individuals who have made a significant contribution to children's literature.\n\n== Books ==\n* ''Der verschlafene Sonntag'', illus. by [[Hermann Gradl]]. W. H\u00e4decke, Stuttgart, 1927. Facsimile edition: Br\u00f6stler, Marktheidenfeld, 1992. {{ISBN|9783927439115}}\n* ''Das Geheimnis vom Kuckuckshof - Eine Detektivgeschichte aus dem Schwarzwald'' 1st ed. London, John Murray, London, 1942.\n* ''Wer ist Lux? Eine Detektivgeschichte f\u00fcr die Jugend'', ill. by [[Paul Flora]]. Ensslin & Laiblin, Reutlingen, 1950.\n* ''Die Katze mit der Brille - Die sch\u00f6nsten Gutenachtgeschichten'', collected by Jella Lepman, ed. by [[Hansj\u00f6rg Schmitthenner]], illus. by Regina Ackermann-Oph\u00fcls. Europa-Verlag, Zurich, Vol. 1, 1951; Vol. 2, 1959. Reprinted Zeitverlag Bucerius, Hamburg, 2006. {{ISBN|9783938899021}}\n* ''Der verhaftete Papagei : die sch\u00f6nsten Gute Nacht Geschichten : neueste Folge'', ed. by Hansj\u00f6rg Schmitthenner, ill. by Jutta Kirsch-Korn. Ullstein, Berlin, 1963. {{ISBN|9783548125343}}\n* ''Die Kinderbuchbr\u00fccke'', S. Fischer, Frankfurt, 1964.\n** ''A Bridge of Children's Books'', transl. by Edith McCormick, forward by J.E. Morpurgo. Leicester: Brockhampton Press, Leicester; American Library Association, New York 1969. {{ISBN|0340032057}}\n** ''A Bridge of Children's Books'', transl. by Edith McCormick, forward by [[Mary Robinson]]. The O'Brien Press, Dublin, 2002, {{ISBN|0-86278-783-1}}\n** ''Kodomo no hon wa sekai no kakehashi'', transl. by Morimoto Manami. Kogumasha, Tokyo, 2002. {{ISBN|9784772190374}}\n** ''Jia qi er tong tu shu de qiao liang'', Zhongguo shao nian er tong chu ban she, Beijing, 2006. {{ISBN|9787500780809}}\n** ''Oerini Chaekui Dali'', transl. by Sun-Ah Kang. Nami Books, Seoul, 2015. {{ISBN|9788996683667}}\n** ''Un Puente de Libros Infantiles'', Creotz, 2017. {{ISBN|978-8494147388}} \n* ''Kinder sehen unsere Welt - Texte und Zeichnungen aus 35 L\u00e4ndern'', collected and edited by Jella Lepman. Ullstein, 1971. {{ISBN|9783550077661}}\n** ''Come i bambini vedono il mondo'', transl. by Amina Pandolfi. Garzanti, Milan, 1972.\n** ''How children see our world : words and pictures from thirty-five countries'', translated from the German by Heide Dugall, designed by Dietmar Meyer and Frank Curcio. Avon Books, New York, 1975. {{ISBN|9780380005291}}\n\n== Awards ==\n* 1957 [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n* 1960 [[Goethe Medal]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lepman, Jella}}\n[[Category:German women journalists]]\n[[Category:People from Stuttgart]]\n[[Category:German children's literature]]\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:German translators]]\n[[Category:20th-century translators]]\n[[Category:20th-century German women writers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Gedenktafel Jella Lepman.jpg|thumb|Memorial plaque for Jella Lepman at the international youth library in Blutenburg castel]]\n\n'''Jella Lepman''' (15 May 1891, in [[Stuttgart]] \u2013 14 October 1970, in [[Zurich]]) was a [[Germany|German]] journalist, author and translator who founded the [[International Youth Library]] in Munich.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.freiburger-rundbrief.de/de/?item=231 | title=Jella Lepman \u2014 Die Kinderbuchbr\u00fccke | author=Ingrid Wei\u00df | date=1995 | website= | publisher=Freiburger Rundbrief | language=German | accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\nJella Lehman, born in [[Stuttgart]], was the oldest daughter of the manufacturer Josef Lehmann (1853-1911) and his wife Flora ([[n\u00e9e]] Lauchheimer; 1867-1940). The family were members of the [[Reform Judaism|Jewish-liberal Judaism]]. Through her mother she was a cousin of the four-year younger [[Max Horkheimer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.juedische-allgemeine.de/unsere-woche/die-kinder-werden-den-weg-zeigen/|title=\u00bbDie Kinder werden den Weg zeigen\u00ab |accessdate=April 1, 2020|date=August 25, 2019|work=J\u00fcdische Allgemeine| author=Diehl, Kathrin |}}</ref> After her schooling at the K\u00f6nigin-Katharina-Stift-Gymnasium in Stuttgart, she spent a year near [[Lausanne]], Switzerland. At the age of 17, in 1908, she organised an international reading room for the children of foreign works at a tobacco factory in an industrial quarter of Stuttgart.\n\nIn 1913 she married Gustav Horace Lepman (1877-1922), the German-American co-owner of a bedspring factory in [[Stuttgart-Feuerbach]]. Together they had two children: (Anne-Marie, born in 1918, G\u00fcnther, born in 1921). During the [[World War I]] Gustav Lepman served as an officer in the German army on the battlefields in France. He died as the result of his war injuries in 1922, leaving her widowed at age 31.\n \nAfter the death of her husband, Jella Lepman became editor of the ''Stuttgarter Neues Tagblatt'', the first woman ever to hold this position. She wrote socio-political contributions and in 1927 introduced the newspaper supplement for women titled  \"The woman in house, profession and society\". In addition, she published her first children's book (1927 ''The Sleeping Sunday'') and a theatrical play for children (1929 ''The Singing Pfennig'') which was performed on the smaller state of the W\u00fcrttemberg State Theatre. She became a member of the [[German Democratic Party]] (''Deutsche Demokratische Partei'', DDP), where she was a leader in the women's group. In 1929, she ran, unsuccessfully, for the German [[Reichstag (Weimar Republic)|Reichstag]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.stadtlexikon-stuttgart.de/article/d6a07d28-640b-4bcb-b202-a823655f6cbd/Jella_Lepman_%281891-1970%29.html | title=Jella Lepman (1891 \u2013 1970) |accessdate=April 1, 2020|date=April 19, 2018| work=Stadtlexikon| author=Ferchl, Irene |language=de}}</ref>\n\nWith the [[Nazi seizure of power]] in 1933, Jella Lepman, as a Jew, lost her job at the newspaper, but was able to continue working for it as a freelancer until 1935. In 1936, she emigrated with her two children via Italy to [[England]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.zeit.de/2013/07/Geschichte-Stuttgart-1921/seite-3 | title=Stuttgart 1921 | author=J\u00f6rg Schweigard | date= | website= | publisher=ZEIT ONLINE | language=German | accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref> With her children cared for in boarding schools, she initially took on freelance journalistic and literary assignments. In 1938 she helped organise the papers of [[Arthur Schnitzler]] which had recently arrived at the [[University of Cambridge]]. Later, she worked for the [[BBC]] and the [[American Broadcasting Station in Europe]] (ABSIE). In 1942 she published a German-language reader titled '' Die Kinder vom Kuckuckshof, eine Detektivgeschichte aus dem Schwarzwald '' for the publisher [[John Murray (publisher)|John Murray]] and in 1943, under the [[pseudonym]] Katherine Thomas, the book '' Women in Nazi Germany ''.\n\n== After the war ==\nAfter the end of [[World War II]], she returned to Germany in October 1945 as a consultant to the [[United States Army|US Army]] as part of the {{ill|Reeducation (denazification)|lt=Reeducation|de|Reeducation}} program of the American occupied zone,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://libreas.eu/ausgabe25/05becchi/ | title=Jella Lepman: Die Gr\u00fcnderin der Internationalen Jugendbibliothek | author=Anna Becchi | date=2014 | website= | publisher=LIBREAS. Library Ideas | language=German | accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref> and responsible for programmes for women and youth. She lived first in [[Bad Homburg vor der H\u00f6he]], then in [[Munich]]. In 1946 she organised the first international exhibition in post-war Germany, the {{ill|Internationale Jugendbuchausstellung |lt=Internationale Jugendbuchausstellung|de|Internationale Jugendbuchausstellung}}, which displayed 2000 books from 14 countries. It was shown in several large cities around Germany and visited by over one million people. These books became the founding collection for the [[International Youth Library]] which was opened in the [[Schwabing]] section of Munich 14 September 1949. She remained its director until her retirement in 1957.\n\nDuring the [[reconstruction of Germany]], she was convinced that placing books into the hands of the children would offer them hope for the future. In 1952 she initiated a conference about international understanding through children's books, which led to the foundation of the non-profit [[International Board on Books for Young People]] in [[Zurich]] in 1953. Lepman wrote more in detail about this time of her life in her autobiographical book ''A Bridge of Children's Books''. She was one of the initiators of the [[Hans Christian Andersen Award]], the world's most important award for writers and illustrators of young people's literature. It was first issued in 1956, and she served as its jury president from 1956 to 1960.\n\nJella Lepman wrote many children\u2019s books and collections of children\u2019s stories, including a multivolume collection of bedtime stories that she collected over the years. Her books have been translated into many different languages. She gave her friend [[Erich K\u00e4stner]] the idea that inspired his children's book ''The Animals' Conference'' (''Die Konferenz der Tiere'', 1949).\n\nLepman died in 1970 at the age of 79 years in Zurich and her final resting place was in the [[Zurich Enzenb\u00fchl cemetery]] on Forchstra\u00dfe. The grave no longer exists.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/prd/de/index/bevoelkerungsamt/tod/friedhoefe/prominente_verstorbene.html | title=Prominente Vorstorbene nach Alphabet (PDF) |accessdate=April 1, 2020|date=March 6, 2020| work=Stadt Z\u00fcrich| language=de}}</ref> There is a street named after her in Stuttgart, and room named after her in Stuttgart's main public library on Mail\u00e4nder-Platz.\n\nSince 1991, in honor of Lepman's 100th birthday, the International Board on Books for Young People awards the \"Jella-Lepman Medal\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=737 | title=Jella Lepman Medal | author= | date= | website= | publisher=International Board on Books for Young People | language= | accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref> to individuals who have made a significant contribution to children's literature.\n\n== Books ==\n* ''Der verschlafene Sonntag'', illus. by [[Hermann Gradl]]. W. H\u00e4decke, Stuttgart, 1927. Facsimile edition: Br\u00f6stler, Marktheidenfeld, 1992. {{ISBN|9783927439115}}\n* ''Das Geheimnis vom Kuckuckshof - Eine Detektivgeschichte aus dem Schwarzwald'' 1st ed. London, John Murray, London, 1942.\n* ''Wer ist Lux? Eine Detektivgeschichte f\u00fcr die Jugend'', ill. by [[Paul Flora]]. Ensslin & Laiblin, Reutlingen, 1950.\n* ''Die Katze mit der Brille - Die sch\u00f6nsten Gutenachtgeschichten'', collected by Jella Lepman, ed. by [[Hansj\u00f6rg Schmitthenner]], illus. by Regina Ackermann-Oph\u00fcls. Europa-Verlag, Zurich, Vol. 1, 1951; Vol. 2, 1959. Reprinted Zeitverlag Bucerius, Hamburg, 2006. {{ISBN|9783938899021}}\n* ''Der verhaftete Papagei : die sch\u00f6nsten Gute Nacht Geschichten : neueste Folge'', ed. by Hansj\u00f6rg Schmitthenner, ill. by Jutta Kirsch-Korn. Ullstein, Berlin, 1963. {{ISBN|9783548125343}}\n* ''Die Kinderbuchbr\u00fccke'', S. Fischer, Frankfurt, 1964.\n** ''A Bridge of Children's Books'', transl. by Edith McCormick, forward by J.E. Morpurgo. Leicester: Brockhampton Press, Leicester; American Library Association, New York 1969. {{ISBN|0340032057}}\n** ''A Bridge of Children's Books'', transl. by Edith McCormick, forward by [[Mary Robinson]]. The O'Brien Press, Dublin, 2002, {{ISBN|0-86278-783-1}}\n** ''Kodomo no hon wa sekai no kakehashi'', transl. by Morimoto Manami. Kogumasha, Tokyo, 2002. {{ISBN|9784772190374}}\n** ''Jia qi er tong tu shu de qiao liang'', Zhongguo shao nian er tong chu ban she, Beijing, 2006. {{ISBN|9787500780809}}\n** ''Oerini Chaekui Dali'', transl. by Sun-Ah Kang. Nami Books, Seoul, 2015. {{ISBN|9788996683667}}\n** ''Un Puente de Libros Infantiles'', Creotz, 2017. {{ISBN|978-8494147388}} \n* ''Kinder sehen unsere Welt - Texte und Zeichnungen aus 35 L\u00e4ndern'', collected and edited by Jella Lepman. Ullstein, 1971. {{ISBN|9783550077661}}\n** ''Come i bambini vedono il mondo'', transl. by Amina Pandolfi. Garzanti, Milan, 1972.\n** ''How children see our world : words and pictures from thirty-five countries'', translated from the German by Heide Dugall, designed by Dietmar Meyer and Frank Curcio. Avon Books, New York, 1975. {{ISBN|9780380005291}}\n\n== Awards ==\n* 1957 [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n* 1960 [[Goethe Medal]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lepman, Jella}}\n[[Category:German women journalists]]\n[[Category:People from Stuttgart]]\n[[Category:German children's literature]]\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:German translators]]\n[[Category:20th-century translators]]\n[[Category:20th-century German women writers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Baekemm", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAfter the war:correction and addition of detail", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jella_Lepman"}
